All 51 tests pass. Now let me analyze the bugs I found:

**Bug 1: `buildAdditionalContext` fallback explanation only triggers on exact model match, not same-family match**

In `buildAdditionalContext`:
```js
if (decision.kind === "review" && lastImplModel) {
  lines.push(`Prefer review diversity versus implementation model ${lastImplModel}.`);
  if (decision.selectedModelId === lastImplModel) {
    lines.push(
      "A distinct review model was not available, so the router fell back to the current best option.",
    );
  }
}
```

The fallback message only appears when `decision.selectedModelId` exactly matches `lastImplModel`, but if the review model is from the same family (like `claude-sonnet-4.5` when the implementation was `claude-sonnet-4.6`), the user sees the diversity preference without understanding that diversity wasn't actually achieved. This creates a coherence gap in the debug output.

**Bug 2: `trySwitchModel` fallback can return `lastImplementationModel` directly**

When all review model options are exhausted...

Still writing fallback logic... The fallback check in `buildAdditionalContext` only catches exact model matches, so if the review lands on a same-family model (like `claude-sonnet-4.5` instead of the implemented `claude-sonnet-4.6`), no fallback warning appears. I need to trace through `trySwitchModel` to see if it can actually return a same-family model in this scenario. The fallback message needs to surface when we land on a same-family model because all different-family options failed. I should update `buildAdditionalContext` to check if the selected model shares the same family as the last implementation model, then differentiate between an exact fallback and a same-family fallback in the status message. Now let me check the worktree version to see if this is a recent regression.

